---
title: Javascript Emulation Library
---

{% extends "layouts/default.jinja" %}

{% block body %}

    <header class="show">
        <div class="container responsive-logo">
            <a class="image" ref="https://github.com/arcanis/virtjs/">
            </a>
        </div>
        <div class="container">
            <div class="logo">
                <a class="image" href="https://github.com/arcanis/virtjs/">
                </a>
            </div>
            <div class="example">
                <div class="inner">
                    <canvas class="screen">
                    </canvas>
                    <div class="tools">
                        <a href="https://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-count="none"></a>
                        <script>!function(d,s,id){var js,fjs=d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0],p=/^http:/.test(d.location)?'http':'https';if(!d.getElementById(id)){js=d.createElement(s);js.id=id;js.src=p+'://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js';fjs.parentNode.insertBefore(js,fjs);}}(document, 'script', 'twitter-wjs');</script>
                        <iframe class="star" src="http://ghbtns.com/github-btn.html?user=arcanis&repo=virtjs&type=watch&count=true" allowtransparency="true" frameborder="0" scrolling="0" width="110" height="20">
                        </iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </header>

    <section class="impact container">
        <h2>Emulators. Emulators everywhere. <a href="/documentation/getting-started/">Start now.</a></h2>
        <p class="lead">Virtjs allows you to create embeddable emulators on a variety of architectures. More than that, it exposes conventioned public API so you can easily plug them into your own projects.
    </section>

    <hr class="mini-rule" />

    <section class="advantages container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-sm-4 opensource">
                <div class="glyphicon glyphicon-globe"></div>
                <h3>Open Source</h3>
                <p>Virtjs is released under the MIT license, giving it free of charge to every open-source project that you could think of. The world is yours!</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-sm-4 modular">
                <div class="glyphicon glyphicon-th"></div>
                <h3>Modular</h3>
                <p>Virtjs aims to give you full leverage on the running emulator. It allows you to write your own devices, should you need it, and to directly wire them into the core engines.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-sm-4 fast">
                <div class="glyphicon glyphicon-tower"></div>
                <h3>Modern</h3>
                <p>Virtjs has been made with the full power of ES6, the next iteration of the Javascript programming language. It gives us a pretty simple source code. We're one of the very first libraries to jump aboard!</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="mini-rule" />

    <section class="container">
        <pre><code>{{ example | highlight | safe }}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <script src="https://jspm.io/traceur@0.0.49.js"></script>
    <script src="https://jspm.io/es6-module-loader@0.7.1.js"></script>
    <script src="https://jspm.io/system@0.6.7.js"></script>

    <script>
        System.paths[ 'virtjs/*' ] = '/virtjs/sources/*.js';
        System.paths[ 'scripts/*' ] = '/scripts/*.js';

        System.import( 'scripts/example' );
    </script>

{% endblock %}
